Here's a typical `MauiProgram.cs` setup:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

namespace MyMauiApp;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder
            .UseMauiApp<App>()
            .ConfigureFonts(fonts =>
            {
                fonts.AddFont("OpenSans-Regular.ttf", "OpenSansRegular");
            });

        // Data service — Singleton
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — Transient
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — Transient
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

#if DEBUG
        builder.Logging.AddDebug();
#endif

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes?**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` / REST calls. One instance avoids socket exhaustion and lets you share cache or auth tokens app-wide. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation creates fresh state. Avoids stale data when the user revisits a page. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Pairs 1-to-1 with their ViewModel. A new page instance each time prevents UI state leaking between navigations. |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateless services, HTTP clients, configuration.
- **Transient** — pages and ViewModels (UI state that should reset).
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET), but useful if you create your own `IServiceScope` for a workflow.

> ⚠️ Never inject a transient or scoped dependency into a singleton — it effectively becomes a singleton too (captured dependency problem).
